06805nam a22010095i 9780823296637DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20212001nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232966377 a10.1515/97808232966372doi  a(DE-B1597)575293  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aSOC0250002bisacsh1 aPerez-Koenig, Rosa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSocial Work in the Era of Devolution :bToward a Just Practice /cRosa Perez-Koenig, Barry Rock. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2021] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (403 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile economic indicators in recent years have shown an unprecedented level of prosperity, social indicators tell a different story: growing economic disparity, increasing numbers of Americans lacking health insurance, increased levels of poverty among our youngest and oldest citizens, and an anti-entitlement political climate that has eroded assistance to those most in need. In this era of “devolution,” the federal government has been increasingly removed from the provision of services and support to vulnerable populations. This book presents a framework for understanding the impact of these developments on the practice of social work. The first section focuses on contemporary social forces, processes, and policy changes and their implications for the social work profession. The second section explores practical issues as they affect selected vulnerable populations. The concluding section describes interventions that have been taking place at grass-roots levels, including community action and interagency collaboration. Thus, this book attempts to integrate policy, practice, organizational, and community perspectives on social work practice with a commitment to social justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBerger, Roni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBetter, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoncher, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrettschneider, Eric B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrickman, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownell, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChernesky, Roslyn H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Carol S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCongress, Elaine P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgrove, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickerson, Sonya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForgey, Mary Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreene, Mary Pender, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGutheil, Irene A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHill, Robert H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Carol P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorenzo, Felix, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMach, Marilynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMendez, Manuel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoynihan, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct